                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d824">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862i.01/275: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan (<persName type="from"
                        >Grew</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-09-06T14:00:00+09:00"
                            >September 6, 1933—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 6—2:07 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>135. Department’s 76, September 5, 5 p.m. The statement under reference appeared
                    in all Tokyo newspapers on September 2nd and may be translated as follows:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The South Sea Islands are administered as a part of Japan’s territory.
                            Thus Japan is free to develop them, and need not be restrained by
                            objections from other countries.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Text by the pouch.<note n="73" xml:id="d824fn73">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
